	{
		"id": "pair_meris_alden_after_ledger",
		"unit_a": "Sister Meris",
		"unit_b": "Brother Alden",
		"title": "The Names That Remain",
		"text": "Meris is staring at a copied list of the dead as if it might pass sentence first. Alden sits beside her without asking permission.\n\n\"I used to believe records were a kind of mercy,\" she says at last. \"Order against oblivion.\"\nAlden nods. \"Sometimes they are.\"\nHer hand tightens around the page. \"And sometimes they are just cleaner ways to keep count of what we allowed.\"\nHe does not rush to contradict her. That, more than anything, breaks her composure.\n\"I can still remember the sound of my own voice saying yes,\" she whispers.\nAlden reaches over, not to take the list away, but to steady the hand holding it. \"Then let memory do what punishment never can,\" he says quietly. \"Let it make you gentler than the person who signed.\" \nMeris closes her eyes. \"I am trying.\"\n\"I know,\" he says. \"That is why I sat down.\"",
