	{
		"id": "pair_hadrien_kaelen_last_standard",
		"unit_a": "Ser Hadrien",
		"unit_b": "Kaelen",
		"title": "The Last Standard",
		"text": "Kaelen has laid an old Dawn banner across a crate, patching a tear no one will ever inspect at parade distance. Hadrien’s spectral form flickers beside him.\n\n\"You still tend our dead cloth,\" the old knight says.\n\"Not yours,\" Kaelen replies. \"Mine. I carried enough of it into the world to owe the work personally.\"\nHadrien studies him with the weary patience of a ghost who has had too much time to regret admiration. \"We taught you to bear symbols before you were ready to question them.\"\nKaelen’s hands stop. \"You taught me how to stand up.\"\n\"And not enough about when to kneel,\" Hadrien says.\nThe silence that follows is full of old ruin.\nThen Kaelen asks, almost like a son who should not still need the answer, \"Was any of it worthy?\"\nHadrien’s voice is very quiet. \"You were. And perhaps, because you survived us badly enough to tell the truth, something of the oath may yet be.\"",
